t’, at the core of which was the belief that a strong relationship between merit and reward would bring about social stability and economic efficiency. Equal opportunity and professional expertise, values embodied by the egalitarian aspirations of Penguin’s publishing ethos, would be the drivers of social and economic progress. But as the social and economic crises of the 1970s took root, many contemporary thinkers and politicians cast doubt on the assumptions that informed meritocratic logic. Britain’s meritocratic moment had passed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aPolitical Studies 2020. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aBritish politics.  aIntellectuals.  aMeritocracy.  aPenguin Books.  aPolitical ideology.  aPolitical thought.  aPublishing.  aSocial change.  aSocial democracy.  aThatcherism.1 aBlackburn, Dean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packagez978311128248040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152612927740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526129277423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526129277/original  a978-3-11-128248-0  Manchester University Press 2020 eBook-Packageb2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles